  <h2>Understand</h2>
  <h3>Day 1</h3>
  <p>
    The team, and leadership, had numerous assumptions to challenge:
    people struggle to find value due to a cluttered product,
    FSS is the only value,
    other features are neglected,
    and even if discovered our users lack knowledge on their usage.
    Leveraging initial assumptions, research and behavioral data,
    the team came away with a specific assumption they wanted to test.
    As the approver, <mark>I approved testing the assumption
    that relevant communication enhances feature and product discovery
    effectiveness.</mark>
  </p>

  <h2>Diverge & Converge</h2>
  <h3>Day 2 & Day 3</h3>
  <p>
    As the team expanded their thinking, I had the privilege of participating in
    crazy-8s. One intriguing suggestion was a bot named
    "Friend Lee" on Dropbox, acting as a fake teammate who learns from your
    actions and guides you. Although deemed too unconventional, it remains an
    idea I love. <mark>By the end of the second day, they selected two solutions
    to test their assumption about relevance.</mark>
  </p>

  <h2>Prototype</h2>
  <h3>Day 4</h3>
  <p>
    On what may be my favorite day, prototype day, the team commenced building
    their ideas using Figma as the chosen prototyping tool.
    <mark>
    The skilled
    designers on the team crafted two relatively polished experiences for
    testing.
    </mark>
    The skilled
    One involved a quiz-based onboarding process that transparently
    gathered insights from customers while reciprocating with valuable feedback.
    The other consisted of a pattern triggered by actions, leading to a workflow
    chain.
  </p>

  <h2>Test</h2>
  <h3>Day 5</h3>
  <p>

    The prototypes underwent testing with 12 customers within a single day. The
    two designers, in collaboration with the research team, conducted
    two distinct tests, each involving six users.
    Active participation and
    note-taking were evident from everyone involved.
    <mark>
    The outcome revealed that
    relevance played a pivotal role.
    </mark>
    Smart suggestions that followed actions
    proved to be effective, and customers were willing to share information if
    they understood it would guide them towards specific actions.
  </p>

  <h2>Success</h2>
  <p>
    The sprint was a success. The team had validated their assumption — “Feature
    and product discovery communication is effective when relevant.“ From here,
    we would start to plan a series of experiments based off of this learning.
  </p>

  <h2>Rinse & Repeat</h2>
  <p>
    After the design sprint we explored fresh
    ways to communicate with our customers, discovered new opportunities to
    engage them, and found different ways to understand their needs.
    <mark>
    By combining Design Sprints and A/B testing,
    we kept iterating and improving.</mark>
    I can even show you a sneak peek of the activation experience,
